WEBVTT

00:00.680 --> 00:05.440
But let's talk a little bit about what we've done here.

00:05.440 --> 00:06.440
We have an order form.

00:06.440 --> 00:08.080
This will eventually will look nicer

00:08.080 --> 00:10.440
once we have like all the pieces put together.

00:14.480 --> 00:17.280
I want you to try and select a different type of pizza.

00:21.500 --> 00:23.360
Doesn't work, right?

00:23.360 --> 00:28.360
It broke the browser, which is actually kind of hard to do, right?

00:28.360 --> 00:32.360
Like the browser works really well at creating these types of forms,

00:32.360 --> 00:35.360
and whatever we did with React made it not work,

00:35.360 --> 00:38.360
which seems kind of counterproductive, right?

00:38.360 --> 00:39.360
Same thing with the pizza size.

00:39.360 --> 00:41.360
Click on one of these other buttons.

00:41.360 --> 00:45.360
No matter what, you're always going to be selecting small or large.

00:47.360 --> 00:48.360
And that's annoying, right?

00:48.360 --> 00:51.360
We expect the radio buttons to work so that you can select small, medium,

00:52.360 --> 00:54.360
or large.

00:54.360 --> 00:57.360
Well, reason with me of why this is happening.

01:00.360 --> 01:01.360
All right.

01:01.360 --> 01:06.360
So you have pepperoni here, right?

01:06.360 --> 01:07.360
Which is the value here.

01:07.360 --> 01:10.360
So that's why it's selecting that one.

01:10.360 --> 01:13.360
Now I click Hawaiian, right?

01:13.360 --> 01:17.360
If I click Hawaiian here, what happens?

01:17.360 --> 01:20.360
React says, hey, an event happened.

01:20.360 --> 01:22.360
The user did something.

01:22.360 --> 01:26.360
It's time for us to re-render this component, right?

01:26.360 --> 01:28.360
So it goes through, and it re-renders this component.

01:28.360 --> 01:31.360
It says, oh, pizza type, pepperoni, right?

01:31.360 --> 01:35.360
And so it sets the value to be pizza type, pepperoni.

01:35.360 --> 01:38.360
So even though the user is clicking on something else,

01:38.360 --> 01:40.360
it's immediately setting it back to where it was,

01:40.360 --> 01:43.360
because this isn't dynamic, right?

01:43.360 --> 01:47.360
This is just assigned, and then it just stays that way.

01:47.360 --> 01:50.360
So we have to do some sort of assigning pizza type

01:50.360 --> 01:53.360
to be something different,

01:53.360 --> 01:57.360
or else it's just going to continually be that.

01:57.360 --> 02:00.360
This is just a roundabout way of me explaining and showing to you

02:00.360 --> 02:04.360
that two-way data binding is not free in React.

02:04.360 --> 02:05.360
There are some other frameworks.

02:05.360 --> 02:07.360
And famously, Angular 1, right,

02:07.360 --> 02:10.360
was a big two-way data binding framework,

02:10.360 --> 02:12.360
and that's just not true anymore.

02:12.360 --> 02:16.360
We found that that's very fun to write and very bad to maintain,

02:16.360 --> 02:18.360
because it becomes very black magic of,

02:18.360 --> 02:22.360
like, where did this variable come from?

02:22.360 --> 02:24.360
It's part of the magic of React is that it is verbose.

02:24.360 --> 02:27.360
I'm not going to argue with you that it is not...

02:27.360 --> 02:32.360
It could be shorter or more terse or something like that.

02:32.360 --> 02:34.360
It's a little less fun to write,

02:34.360 --> 02:37.360
and it's a lot more fun to maintain.

02:37.360 --> 02:38.360
And as I've gone through my career,

02:38.360 --> 02:42.360
I have found that that's actually worth its weight in gold, right?

02:43.360 --> 02:46.360
I don't want to optimize for the couple of hours

02:46.360 --> 02:47.360
I'm going to spend writing something.

02:47.360 --> 02:49.360
I want to optimize for the hundreds of hours

02:49.360 --> 02:53.360
I'm going to spend maintaining something.

02:53.360 --> 02:56.360
Okay, so that's my spiel of why I think this is okay,

02:56.360 --> 03:01.360
despite the fact that it is a little annoying.

03:01.360 --> 03:03.360
Interesting if you go try something like Solid.js,

03:03.360 --> 03:06.360
which is very similar to React in many ways.

03:06.360 --> 03:10.360
They found a way to kind of make it work with something called signals.

03:10.360 --> 03:12.360
I think signals are in Preact as well now.

03:12.360 --> 03:14.360
I haven't worked in Preact in a long time.

03:14.360 --> 03:17.360
But anyway, suffice to say,

03:17.360 --> 03:19.360
other frameworks have different approaches to this,

03:19.360 --> 03:22.360
but React takes a very straightforward, very...

03:22.360 --> 03:24.360
I want to call it JavaScript-y,

03:24.360 --> 03:27.360
that they're just kind of working with JavaScript

03:27.360 --> 03:30.360
to make it work the way that JavaScript normally works,

03:30.360 --> 03:32.360
as opposed to having black magic around the framework

03:32.360 --> 03:34.360
to make it work differently.

03:34.360 --> 03:39.360
So let's go make this work with state then, right?

03:39.360 --> 03:42.360
We're going to use something called a hook,

03:42.360 --> 03:49.360
and we're going to do this thing called import use state from React.

03:49.360 --> 03:52.360
Anything that you see use in React,

03:52.360 --> 03:56.360
the alarm should go off in your head, it's like, this is a hook.

03:56.360 --> 03:59.360
Okay?

03:59.360 --> 04:02.360
So instead of these two,

04:02.360 --> 04:09.360
let's say const pizza type set pizza type

04:09.360 --> 04:14.360
equals use state,

04:14.360 --> 04:20.360
and then you give it the default first value, pepperoni.

04:20.360 --> 04:22.360
Same thing with pizza size.

04:22.360 --> 04:29.360
const pizza size set pizza size

04:29.360 --> 04:32.360
equals use state,

04:32.360 --> 04:34.360
and whatever you want the default to be.

04:34.360 --> 04:36.360
We had it as medium, we'll just leave it as medium,

04:36.360 --> 04:38.360
but you could change it to large if, I don't know,

04:38.360 --> 04:43.360
you're trying to drive up your margins or something like that.

04:43.360 --> 04:45.360
This is also, of course, on capitalism.

04:45.360 --> 04:48.360
I don't know if I told you that, but...

04:48.360 --> 04:50.360
All right.

04:50.360 --> 04:55.360
So now we have this use state thing,

04:55.360 --> 04:59.360
but this now makes pizza type able to be set to be something different.

04:59.360 --> 05:01.360
It makes this React component stateful,

05:01.360 --> 05:06.360
but we still have to call this set pizza type somewhere

05:06.360 --> 05:09.360
so that we can change it.

05:09.360 --> 05:14.360
So the way that we're going to do it is we're going to go on our select here.

05:14.360 --> 05:19.360
By the way, these are just highlighted because they're not being used anywhere,

05:19.360 --> 05:22.360
but we'll do that in just a second.

05:22.360 --> 05:24.360
All right.

05:24.360 --> 05:28.360
So I'm just going to put some space here so you can see what I'm writing.

05:28.360 --> 05:32.360
We'll do something here called on change,

05:32.360 --> 05:38.360
and the only thing we're going to do is we're going to say

05:38.360 --> 05:42.360
E, which is like a normal browser event, right?

05:42.360 --> 05:44.360
You could call this event.

05:44.360 --> 05:47.360
Just for so many years of doing this, I just always call it E,

05:47.360 --> 05:50.360
so that's really up to you.

05:50.360 --> 05:53.360
And we're just going to give this anonymous function that says

05:53.360 --> 05:59.360
set pizza type to be E.target.value.

06:03.360 --> 06:09.360
So this is saying whenever a change event happens on select,

06:09.360 --> 06:11.360
call this function.

06:11.360 --> 06:15.360
This function takes in an event,

06:15.360 --> 06:18.360
and it calls set pizza type with the target.value.

06:18.360 --> 06:21.360
The target is going to be one of these options, right,

06:21.360 --> 06:23.360
because that's what's actually going to be the,

06:23.360 --> 06:26.360
well, I think the target is actually the select, not thinking about it,

06:26.360 --> 06:29.360
but the value will change, right?

06:29.360 --> 06:31.360
So the value will be whatever the option is,

06:31.360 --> 06:33.360
so this value will be whatever the user has set,

06:33.360 --> 06:35.360
and we'll call that with set pizza type,

06:35.360 --> 06:38.360
which will then end up changing the pizza type up here,

06:38.360 --> 06:40.360
which kicks off a re-render,

06:40.360 --> 06:45.360
and now it's going to be correctly rendering the same thing.

06:45.360 --> 06:48.360
So if we set this, size is still not going to work,

06:48.360 --> 06:51.360
we haven't done that yet, but let's go try this one.

06:51.360 --> 06:56.360
We should be able to set this to something else.

06:56.360 --> 07:01.360
Congratulations, we un-broke it, right?

07:01.360 --> 07:06.360
All right, so this is called a hook.

07:06.360 --> 07:09.360
Some rules around Fight Club.

07:09.360 --> 07:11.360
We don't talk about Fight Club.

07:11.360 --> 07:15.360
Some rules around hooks.

07:15.360 --> 07:21.360
You do talk about hooks, you can talk about hooks, that's fine.

07:21.360 --> 07:23.360
They can never be inside of conditionals,

07:23.360 --> 07:25.360
so never ever do something like this.

07:25.360 --> 07:30.360
If something, right, then use state.

07:30.360 --> 07:34.360
This is a big no-no because the one thing about hooks

07:34.360 --> 07:38.360
is that they depend on being called in the same order every single time.

07:38.360 --> 07:41.360
So if I did a conditional there,

07:41.360 --> 07:45.360
then it would sometimes give them to me out of order,

07:45.360 --> 07:48.360
so really what would happen is sometimes medium would show up in pizza type,

07:48.360 --> 07:51.360
which is not what you want.

07:51.360 --> 07:57.360
So, in other words, hooks never go inside of for loops,

07:57.360 --> 08:02.360
while loops, do loops, they never go inside of conditionals,

08:02.360 --> 08:04.360
they're just always top level.

08:04.360 --> 08:06.360
Even if you don't use them, that's fine,

08:06.360 --> 08:08.360
you just never put them in conditionals.

08:08.360 --> 08:12.360
You never have to, so sometimes you ignore a hook and that's fine,

08:12.360 --> 08:16.360
but you still have to call it in the same order every single time.

08:16.360 --> 08:23.360
There's linting rules that will help you with that as well.

08:23.360 --> 08:25.360
So why are they called hooks?

08:25.360 --> 08:30.360
In my head canon of why this is, I've never asked anyone this,

08:30.360 --> 08:33.360
this is just what occurs to me, is there's a hook

08:33.360 --> 08:35.360
that gets called in the same order every single time,

08:35.360 --> 08:37.360
so it's like a hook being picked up,

08:37.360 --> 08:40.360
and they get picked up in the same order every single time

08:40.360 --> 08:46.360
in these render functions.

08:46.360 --> 08:51.360
Yep, hooks rely on strict ordering, we talked about that.

08:51.360 --> 08:53.360
Oh yeah, some of you might be thinking,

08:53.360 --> 08:55.360
this seems like a weird API, right?

08:55.360 --> 08:57.360
It is kind of a weird API if you think about it,

08:57.360 --> 09:00.360
I'm just so used to seeing it so frequently that, again,

09:00.360 --> 09:03.360
I'm a frog that got boiled, right?

09:03.360 --> 09:07.360
But it's just returning to you an array of two things,

09:07.360 --> 09:11.360
the actual thing and then the setter for the actual thing, right?

09:11.360 --> 09:14.360
That's just all that is, right?

09:14.360 --> 09:24.360
So you could definitely say like const pizza hook equals use state, right?

09:24.360 --> 09:36.360
And then you would say const pizza type equals pizza hook zero,

09:36.360 --> 09:44.360
and then set pizza type, right?

09:44.360 --> 09:50.360
This one line is the equivalent of these three lines,

09:50.360 --> 09:56.360
but we're all very lazy and we all write it this way.

09:56.360 --> 10:00.360
Use state is by far the most common one that you will use,

10:00.360 --> 10:03.360
but I will show you a couple other hooks,

10:03.360 --> 10:08.360
but just know that use state is by far the most common one.

10:08.360 --> 10:11.360
Someone online is just asking if you could console log

10:11.360 --> 10:14.360
just to show kind of the state changing.

10:14.360 --> 10:23.360
Sure.

10:23.360 --> 10:28.360
Type, pizza size.

10:28.360 --> 10:31.360
All right.

10:31.360 --> 10:38.360
Let's just trash this.

10:38.360 --> 10:43.360
So you can see every time that a user event is happening here,

10:43.360 --> 10:47.360
it's actually doing a re-render.

10:47.360 --> 10:51.360
It's interesting that it is smart enough to know that events happening

10:51.360 --> 10:55.360
in other parts of the DOM are not being observed,

10:55.360 --> 10:58.360
and so it's not catching those events.

10:58.360 --> 11:00.360
React has gotten a lot smarter over the years.

11:00.360 --> 11:03.360
They used to have triggered a re-render and it doesn't anymore.

11:03.360 --> 11:12.360
So let's go make it work with pizza size as well.

11:12.360 --> 11:18.360
So with pizza size, there's a couple different ways to do this.

11:18.360 --> 11:24.360
I'll show you the lazy way that the linter will complain about.

11:24.360 --> 11:29.360
Event bubbling still works in React as well.

11:29.360 --> 11:35.360
So in theory, you can actually do it this way.

11:35.360 --> 11:55.360
Equals same thing, E set pizza size to be E.target.value.

11:55.360 --> 11:57.360
And then this will start working, right,

11:57.360 --> 12:01.360
we have one event listener on the parent element, right,

12:01.360 --> 12:04.360
and so it's listening for just the one time.

12:04.360 --> 12:08.360
React doesn't like this because it views it as inaccessible,

12:08.360 --> 12:12.360
which generally you don't want change handlers on like divs

12:12.360 --> 12:16.360
because screen readers and all that kind of stuff can't access divs,

12:16.360 --> 12:20.360
they access inputs, right.

12:20.360 --> 12:22.360
I think in this particular case it wouldn't matter

12:22.360 --> 12:24.360
because it's still bubbling the event no matter what,

12:24.360 --> 12:28.360
and so you can have a change event on a input and it'll still work.

12:28.360 --> 12:33.360
But let's just appease the linting gods

12:33.360 --> 12:38.360
and we're going to put this on all the individual inputs.

12:38.360 --> 12:43.360
It's more explicit as well, so we're just going to put this

12:43.360 --> 12:48.360
three different times on all of these.

12:48.360 --> 12:51.360
Now you might say like, well, do I need E.target.value

12:51.360 --> 12:56.360
or should I do S here like this?

12:56.360 --> 13:01.360
Tomato, tomato, same thing.

13:01.360 --> 13:06.360
Because the value is coming from here, right.

13:06.360 --> 13:09.360
But in both cases it works.

